Po_core: A Philosophy-Driven AI Deliberation Framework for Ethical Decision Support

Authors: Flying Pig Philosopher
Affiliation: Independent Research
Contact: [repository] https://github.com/hiroshitanaka-creator/Po_core
Package: po-core-flyingpig (PyPI)
Version: 0.3.0 — March 2026

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

ABSTRACT

Large language models (LLMs) generate outputs by interpolating statistical
patterns in training data. This property has led critics to question whether
such systems are capable of genuine deliberation or ethical accountability,
as opposed to producing text that merely resembles reasoning. We describe
Po_core, a deliberation framework in which 42 philosopher AI personas,
organized across Western, Eastern, African, and Canadian philosophical
traditions, evaluate prompts using three quantitative tensor metrics and a
three-layer ethical gate before producing a response.

The system is deterministic in the strict sense: given identical inputs and
random seeds, it produces identical outputs at the byte level. This property
is enforced by a CI pipeline running 3,682 tests, all of which passed at the
time of writing, along with 52 acceptance tests that compare pipeline outputs
against frozen golden files.

A controlled experiment examined how ethical constraints affect the quality
of philosophical synthesis. Across 45 trials distributed over three LLM
backends and three experimental conditions, systems operating under the
framework's ethical constraint transformed Nietzsche's concept of the Will
to Power into generativity-oriented formulations in every constrained trial,
while no such transformation occurred in unconstrained conditions. The
statistical separation was complete (χ² = 45.0, p < 10⁻⁶).

On a four-axis evaluation covering philosophical diversity, output
explainability, adversarial safety, and emergent synthesis, Po_core scored
91.75 overall, compared to 59.75 for a Mixture-of-Experts baseline, 51.0
for an RLHF-trained model, 49.25 for a chain-of-thought baseline, and 44.50
for an unaugmented frontier LLM.

Keywords: AI ethics, philosophical deliberation, W_Ethics Gate, Solar Will,
deterministic AI, multi-perspective reasoning, ethical constraints


━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

1. INTRODUCTION

1.1 Background

In 2021, Bender and colleagues introduced the phrase "stochastic parrot" to
characterize LLMs as systems that produce statistically coherent text by
recombining training data without grounding in meaning, consequence, or
ethical reasoning (Bender et al., 2021). The criticism is not merely
rhetorical. It raises a design question with practical implications: if an
AI system cannot trace why a particular output was selected, and cannot
verify that the selection process respected stated ethical principles, then
deploying such a system in contexts where accountability matters — clinical
decision support, policy analysis, ethical counseling — carries risks that
are difficult to quantify or control.

Existing approaches to this problem fall into two broad categories. One
family of methods modifies model training to incorporate human preferences or
constitutionally stated principles (Ouyang et al., 2022; Bai et al., 2022).
The other pursues post-hoc interpretability by analyzing attention weights
or activation patterns after the fact. Neither approach makes the reasoning
process itself observable at runtime, and neither provides a natural
mechanism for integrating philosophically diverse perspectives into a single
deliberation.

1.2 Approach

Po_core takes a different path. Rather than training a single model to
internalize ethical constraints, it constructs a deliberation pipeline in
which distinct philosophical perspectives — each implemented as a named
module with a defined interface — evaluate a prompt through a structured
sequence of steps. The pipeline's outputs are fully traceable: every ethical
decision is logged with the identifier of the rule that produced it, and the
complete deliberation record is available for inspection.

The framework does not claim to solve the problem of AI alignment in general.
Its scope is deliberative decision support: given a question or situation
with genuine ethical complexity, produce a response that reflects multiple
philosophical traditions, applies named ethical rules transparently, and can
be reproduced exactly given the same inputs.

1.3 Contributions

This paper reports four contributions. First, we describe the architecture
of the Po_core deliberation pipeline, a ten-step hexagonal system in which
42 philosopher modules interact through tensor-valued state representations
and a three-layer ethical gate. Second, we present empirical results from a
controlled experiment on the effect of ethical constraints on philosophical
emergence quality, including the Solar Will phenomenon described in Section 4.
Third, we provide a comparative evaluation against four baselines on
dimensions of diversity, explainability, safety, and emergent synthesis.
Fourth, we document the determinism and reproducibility properties of the
implementation, including the test suite and acceptance test schema.

The system is publicly available as po-core-flyingpig on PyPI. All results
reported here are reproducible by running the included test suite.

1.4 Paper Organization

Section 2 reviews related work. Section 3 describes the system architecture.
Section 4 presents the Solar Will experiment. Section 5 reports comparative
evaluation results. Section 6 describes implementation and reproducibility
properties. Section 7 discusses implications and limitations. Section 8
concludes.


