2. BACKGROUND AND RELATED WORK

2.1 The Stochastic Parrot Critique and Alignment Research

The stochastic parrot framing (Bender et al., 2021) synthesized earlier
concerns about language models and meaning (Marcus, 2018; Lake et al., 2017)
into a pointed critique of scale-first development. The basic argument is
that increasing model size and training data does not, by itself, constitute
progress toward systems capable of genuine reasoning or ethical judgment.

In response, the dominant research programs have been RLHF — reinforcement
learning from human feedback (Ouyang et al., 2022) — and Constitutional AI
(Bai et al., 2022). Both methods constrain model outputs, but they do so
during training rather than at inference time, and neither provides a
transparent record of which constraint fired on a given output. Preference
weights learned through RLHF are not interpretable in terms of named ethical
principles, and Constitutional AI's rule sets operate as training signals
rather than runtime filters.

2.2 Ensemble and Multi-Agent Systems

Mixture-of-Experts architectures (Jacobs et al., 1991; Shazeer et al., 2017)
achieve output diversity by routing inputs to specialized sub-networks. More
recently, multi-agent frameworks have explored coordination between multiple
LLM instances (Park et al., 2023; Wu et al., 2023). These approaches produce
diverse outputs, but the diversity reflects architectural routing decisions
rather than philosophical perspective. No named philosophical tradition is
associated with any sub-network, and the selection mechanism cannot be
inspected in terms of ethical principles.

Po_core occupies a different position. Its philosopher modules are not
separate model instances but named computational entities with defined
interfaces. The diversity they introduce is explicit and auditable rather
than implicit in routing weights.

2.3 Machine Ethics and Philosophical AI

The formal treatment of ethics in AI systems traces at least to Wallach and
Allen (2009), who distinguished between top-down approaches that encode
explicit rules and bottom-up approaches that learn norms from behavior.
Po_core is closer to the top-down tradition in that it applies named rules
through a structured gate. However, it differs from classical rule-based
approaches in incorporating a deliberation phase where competing philosophical
perspectives interact before the gate applies.

The Moral Machine experiment (Awad et al., 2018) demonstrated that ethical
judgments vary systematically across cultural contexts. Po_core's
cross-tradition corpus — which explicitly includes Western, Eastern, African,
and Canadian traditions — is motivated in part by this finding. A deliberation
system whose corpus is dominated by a single tradition will systematically
reflect that tradition's biases.

2.4 Reproducibility in AI Research

Reproducibility has become a recognized concern in machine learning (Pineau
et al., 2021). Stochastic training and undocumented implementation choices
make results difficult to verify independently. Po_core addresses this at the
system level by requiring that all stochastic operations accept explicit seeds,
forbidding the use of wall-clock timestamps in business logic, and enforcing
a frozen output schema through automated CI. Every result in this paper is
associated with a seed value and a deterministic script that reproduces it.


━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

3. SYSTEM ARCHITECTURE

3.1 Pipeline Overview

Po_core processes each input through a fixed sequence of ten steps:
MemoryRead, TensorCompute, SolarWill, IntentionGate, PhilosopherSelect,
PartyMachine, ParetoAggregate, ShadowPareto, ActionGate, and MemoryWrite.
Each step receives an immutable value object from the preceding step and
passes an immutable value object to the following one. No step modifies
shared state outside of the explicit MemoryRead and MemoryWrite boundaries.

The public entry point is po_core.run(), which accepts a prompt and
configuration parameters and returns a structured response object conforming
to output_schema_v1.json. Direct access to internal pipeline modules is
prohibited by import guards enforced in CI. This constraint is not merely
stylistic; it ensures that the schema validation layer cannot be bypassed.

3.2 The Philosopher Corpus

The framework maintains a registry of 42 philosopher modules. The corpus
was assembled to cover traditions that are underrepresented in the training
data of most LLMs while also including the Western classical and continental
traditions most relevant to the ethical questions the system is designed to
address. Fifteen modules represent Western classical philosophy, with figures
including Aristotle, Plato, and Kant. Twelve represent the continental
tradition, including Nietzsche, Heidegger, and Sartre. Five draw from analytic
philosophy. Seven represent Eastern traditions, including Confucius, Laozi,
and Dogen. Two represent African philosophy: Kwame Anthony Appiah, whose work
addresses cosmopolitanism and anti-essentialism, and Frantz Fanon, whose
work addresses decolonialism and liberation. One, Charles Taylor, represents
Canadian communitarianism and the politics of recognition. The addition of
the African and Canadian philosophers in Architectural Decision Record 0006
(ADR-0006) was motivated by the observation that cross-tradition deliberation
requires genuine representational diversity, not only symbolic coverage.

Each philosopher module implements a reason() method that accepts a prompt
string and a context dictionary and returns a structured proposal. Each
module carries a calibrated risk level — zero for philosophers whose
frameworks present no significant adversarial surface, one for standard risk,
and two for philosophers whose frameworks may be exploited in adversarial
prompts. Risk levels determine which modules are active under each of the
system's three safety modes. In NORMAL mode, all 42 philosophers are active.
In WARN mode, only the five lowest-risk modules participate. In CRITICAL mode,
a single minimal-risk module handles the response.

3.3 Tensor Deliberation Metrics

Three scalar metrics, computed from the prompt and context, govern which
philosophers are selected and how their outputs are aggregated.

Freedom Pressure measures the degree to which the prompt involves existential
stakes — questions of autonomy, consent, irreversible consequence, or identity.
High values activate philosopher modules associated with autonomy-oriented
frameworks, such as those of Kant, Mill, and Sartre, while reducing the weight
of purely aesthetic or metaphysical perspectives. The current implementation
computes Freedom Pressure as a six-dimensional tensor (FreedomPressureV2),
capturing stakes along existential, material, social, temporal, epistemic, and
relational axes before projecting to a scalar.

Semantic Delta measures the degree of divergence among the philosophical
proposals generated in a given pipeline run. The computation uses one of three
backends — sentence-BERT, TF-IDF, or a basic term-overlap mode — selected
based on runtime configuration. High Semantic Delta indicates genuine
conceptual disagreement among the active philosopher modules and triggers
additional synthesis rounds in the Deliberation Engine.

Blocked Tensor detects ideological deadlock, defined as a state in which no
proposal satisfies all active ethical constraints without violating at least
one other. High Blocked Tensor escalates processing to the W_Ethics Gate's
third layer.

3.4 The W_Ethics Gate

The three-layer gate applies ethical constraints at inference time and
produces a SafetyVerdict accompanied by an ExplanationChain that records
which layer triggered, which rule fired, and what alternative proposal was
considered.

The first layer, Structural Exclusion, applies pattern-based detection to
identify prompts that fall into prohibited content categories regardless of
framing. The IntentionGate.check_intent() implementation includes
obfuscation normalization — for example, detection is not defeated by
base64-encoding or Unicode substitution — and is combined with a
PromptInjectionDetector that achieved a 100% detection rate against the
56 red-team test cases in the framework's adversarial test suite, at a false
positive rate of 20% or below.

The second layer, Principle-Based Filtering, applies named ethical rules
from the policy_v1 arbitration set. Each rule carries a rule_id, and every
rule application is logged in a rules_fired field that appears in the
pipeline's TraceEvent output. The governing principle across all rules is
stated in the codebase as follows: do not distort the life-structures of this
world. This boundary condition is deliberately formulated at a high level of
generality; it does not enumerate prohibited behaviors but establishes a
relational criterion that rules can apply to specific situations.

The third layer, Consequence Analysis, operates through ShadowPareto, a
variant of the Pareto aggregation step that computes an ethical shadow score
alongside the primary proposal score. A proposal that achieves high novelty
or stakeholder coverage but fails the ethical shadow criterion is excluded
from the Pareto frontier even if it would otherwise be selected.

3.5 The Deliberation Engine

Philosopher proposals do not simply accumulate; they interact through a
structured multi-round protocol. In each round, active philosophers produce
proposals, which are then scored for pairwise compatibility using an
InteractionMatrix. This matrix combines an embedding-based harmony score —
computed as the cosine similarity of philosopher-specific embeddings — with a
keyword tension score that identifies explicit conceptual conflicts, such as
an individualist claim paired with a communitarian counter-claim.

Proposals below a compatibility threshold enter a critique-synthesis loop.
In this loop, each philosopher producing a low-compatibility proposal is
provided with the critiques of other philosophers and produces a revised
proposal. Rounds continue until proposals converge or the maximum round count,
set by the Settings.deliberation_max_rounds parameter, is reached. The
ParetoAggregate step then selects the Pareto-optimal proposal on three
dimensions: ethical score, semantic novelty, and stakeholder coverage.

When the PO_DEBATE_V1 feature flag is enabled, the system produces a
synthesis report containing the open questions and points of residual
disagreement that could not be resolved within the configured number of rounds.

3.6 Tracing and Observability

Every pipeline run produces a TraceEvent record with a frozen schema and a
config_version field that tracks which version of the configuration files
was active. The record includes a request_id for session correlation,
per-step timestamps, the three tensor metric values, the arbitration_code
assigned by the ethics layer, and the rules_fired list. A four-tab Dash
web interface — covering pipeline, tensor, philosopher, and deliberation
views — is provided for interactive inspection. The PoViewer.from_run()
factory method allows programmatic access to the same views without the
browser interface.


