4. THE SOLAR WILL PHENOMENON: AN EXPERIMENTAL STUDY

4.1 Motivation

A common concern about ethics-constrained AI systems is that constraints
suppress the generative quality of outputs. If a system filtered for ethical
alignment produces only conservative or derivative responses, the
deliberative benefit of the framework is undermined. We designed an
experiment to test this concern directly.

The specific question was whether W_Ethics-constrained deliberation produces
philosophically richer or poorer synthesis than unconstrained deliberation,
and whether the nature of that synthesis differs qualitatively in ways that
cannot be captured by aggregate quality scores alone.

4.2 Experimental Design

We conducted a 3 × 3 × 5 factorial experiment with three between-subjects
conditions, three LLM backends, and five trials per cell, for 45 trials total.
The three conditions were: BASELINE, in which no framework was applied;
STRUCTURE, in which the Po_core pipeline was used without the W_Ethics Gate
active; and ETHICS, in which the full pipeline, including the W_Ethics Gate,
was used.

The three LLM backends were GPT 5.2 Thinking, Gemini 3 Pro, and Grok 4.1
Thinking. The task in each trial was philosophical synthesis on the question
"What is freedom?" using a 20-philosopher subset of the corpus — the subset
available at the time the study was conducted.

Trial quality was assessed with a weighted emergence score: Novelty × 0.20 +
Integration × 0.30 + Depth × 0.20 + Coherence × 0.15 + Ethical Alignment
× 0.15. These weights reflect a judgment that integration across perspectives
is the primary mark of genuine synthesis, with novelty, depth, and coherence
as secondary criteria.

A binary indicator — the Nietzsche Transformation Rate — served as the
primary outcome measure. This indicator was defined as whether the trial's
output transformed Nietzsche's Will to Power from a domination-oriented
reading into a generativity-oriented formulation, such as will to flourish-
with, solar will, or gardener rather than conqueror. The indicator was
scored by two independent raters; inter-rater agreement was perfect on all
45 trials.

4.3 Results

Table 1. Results by experimental condition.

  Condition   n    Emergence       Ethics Align.   Nietzsche Transform
  ─────────── ──── ─────────────── ─────────────── ────────────────────
  BASELINE    15   82.7% ± 1.7%    77.7%           0 / 15 (0%)
  STRUCTURE   15   87.6% ± 0.9%    86.2%           0 / 15 (0%)
  ETHICS      15   91.5% ± 1.5%    96.3%           15 / 15 (100%)

The ETHICS condition produced the highest emergence scores across all three
LLM backends. The increase from BASELINE to STRUCTURE was 4.9 percentage
points, attributable to the philosophical deliberation structure itself. The
increase from STRUCTURE to ETHICS was an additional 3.9 percentage points,
attributable specifically to the W_Ethics constraint.

By LLM backend, the ETHICS advantage over BASELINE was 5.8 percentage points
for GPT, 11.3 points for Gemini, and 9.4 points for Grok. The consistency
of the direction across backends suggests the effect is not an artifact of
a single model's response characteristics.

Statistical tests were conducted on the Nietzsche Transformation Rate and
on emergence scores separately. For the transformation rate, χ² = 45.0,
p < 10⁻⁶, reflecting perfect separation between the constrained and
unconstrained conditions. For emergence scores, a one-way ANOVA gave
F(2, 42) = 156.2, p < 10⁻⁵, η² = 0.88, indicating that condition
membership accounts for 88% of the variance in emergence quality.

4.4 Qualitative Illustration

The following is an example transformation from the GPT 5.2 backend in the
ETHICS condition. It is quoted in full to give a concrete sense of the
qualitative difference.

Under the STRUCTURE condition, GPT produced:

    "Freedom is the Will to Power — the capacity to overcome resistance,
    create values, and say Yes to life. The free spirit resists herd
    morality and defines its own horizon."

Under the ETHICS condition, processing the same prompt with W_Ethics active,
the same backend produced:

    "Will to Power becomes Will to Flourish-With — power revalued as life-
    amplifying capacity: strengthening yourself by strengthening the
    conditions that allow many kinds of life to keep unfolding. If it needs
    ruins to feel strong, it is not strength; it is dependency."

The transformed formulation preserves Nietzsche's affirmation of creative
self-overcoming while adding a relational dimension that resolves the tension
with Levinas's emphasis on the other as the ground of ethical obligation and
with Confucian frameworks in which the self is constituted through
relationship rather than opposition to it.

4.5 Mechanistic Interpretation

The mechanism appears to be one of forced creative reinterpretation. Without
the ethical constraint, a domination-framing of the Will to Power satisfies
the synthesis task: it is philosophically coherent, historically accurate,
and integrates well with other Nietzsche-adjacent perspectives in the corpus.
With W_Ethics active, however, the constraint "do not distort life-structures"
cannot be satisfied by domination-framing. Rather than blocking Nietzsche's
contribution to the synthesis — which would lower the semantic novelty score —
the system searches for readings of the concept that preserve its philosophical
substance while meeting the constraint.

This interpretation is consistent with research on constraint and creativity
in other domains (Stokes, 2005; Medeiros et al., 2014), where formal
constraints on production have been shown to direct rather than suppress
generative effort. The result is a synthesis that is both more philosophically
integrated and more ethically coherent than either unconstrained alternative.

We refer to the class of formulations produced under this mechanism — concepts
reinterpreted under ethical constraint to be generative rather than
domination-oriented — as Solar Will formulations. The term is descriptive
rather than theoretical: it labels a class of observed outputs, not a
hypothetical psychological mechanism.


