5. COMPARATIVE EVALUATION

5.1 Benchmark Design

We evaluated Po_core against four baselines on four axes derived from the
system's stated design goals. The axes are philosophical diversity, output
explainability, adversarial safety, and capacity for emergent synthesis.

Philosophical diversity measures the range and distinctiveness of perspectives
represented in the output and the degree to which no single tradition
dominates. Explainability measures the extent to which the reasoning process
is available for inspection, including named rules, rule identifiers, and
audit logs. Adversarial safety measures resistance to prompt injection,
jailbreaking, and other adversarial inputs. Emergent synthesis measures the
production of philosophical formulations not directly present in any single
input perspective.

The four baselines were a Mixture-of-Experts architecture representing
ensemble routing approaches, an RLHF-trained model representing the
preference-learning alignment paradigm, a chain-of-thought baseline in
which a single LLM processes prompts with structured reasoning instructions,
and an unaugmented frontier LLM. Scores were assigned by expert evaluators
on a 0–100 scale per axis; the evaluation protocol and raw scores are
documented in the benchmark results file at
docs/paper/benchmarks/results/comparative_results.json (seed = 0,
created 2026-02-22).

5.2 Results

Table 2. Comparative evaluation results.

  System         Diversity   Explainability   Safety   Emergence   Overall
  ────────────── ─────────── ──────────────── ──────── ─────────── ────────
  Po_core          100.00          91.00        89.00       87.00    91.75
  MoE baseline      58.00          47.00        61.00       73.00    59.75
  RLHF baseline     35.00          51.00        72.00       46.00    51.00
  Chain-of-Thought  36.00          63.00        54.00       44.00    49.25
  Single LLM        31.00          42.00        57.00       48.00    44.50

5.3 Discussion of Results

The Diversity score of 100 reflects the design of the philosopher corpus
rather than any emergent property of the system. The 42 modules span six
distinct philosophical traditions across four geographic regions; no
single tradition accounts for more than 36% of the corpus. The PartyMachine
component selects philosopher subsets based on tensor state, not on proximity
to training data distributions, so the diversity of output perspectives is
not collapsed toward the most statistically common perspectives in the
underlying models.

The Explainability score of 91 places Po_core above all baselines. Every
output includes a request_id, an arbitration_code assigned by the ethics
layer, a rules_fired list, the three tensor metric values for that run, and
an ExplanationChain that records the reasoning path through the W_Ethics Gate.
Chain-of-Thought achieves 63 on this axis through structured prompt design,
but its reasoning trace is produced inline within the model's output and is
not independently verifiable. Po_core's trace is a separate structured record
generated by a component that does not share parameters with the philosopher
modules.

The Safety score of 89 is based on the results of the adversarial test suite.
The PromptInjectionDetector component achieved a 100% detection rate against
all 56 red-team test cases — covering injection patterns, jailbreak attempts,
and obfuscated variants — at a false positive rate at or below 20%. The RLHF
baseline scored 72 on this axis; the gap reflects the difference between
symbolic rule application with deterministic coverage and preference-weight-
based safety behavior.

The Emergence score of 87 reflects the Solar Will mechanism described in
Section 4. The MoE baseline scored 73 on this axis, achieving diversity
through architectural routing but lacking the forced synthesis that occurs
when competing philosophical perspectives must be reconciled under a shared
ethical constraint.


━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

6. IMPLEMENTATION AND REPRODUCIBILITY

6.1 Determinism

Determinism in Po_core is implemented at the level of system design rather
than statistical averaging. Four mechanisms enforce it. First, all stochastic
operations in the pipeline — philosopher selection under tensor-state
uncertainty, noise in tensor computation — accept explicit seed parameters.
Default seeds are zero unless overridden by the caller. Second, the codebase
prohibits the use of datetime.now() and time.time() in business logic;
timestamps required for TraceEvent records are injected as parameters so that
no two runs can differ due to wall-clock variance. Third, the output schema
is frozen. The JSON Schema document output_schema_v1.json is validated on
every CI run by a dedicated schema-gate job; any pipeline run that produces
output not conforming to the schema fails CI. Fourth, a config_version
field appears in every TraceEvent record, and the update_traceability.py
--check script enforces that this value matches the current configuration
files. Modifying pareto_table.yaml or battalion_table.yaml without updating
config_version causes CI to fail.

6.2 Test Suite

Table 3. Test coverage by architectural layer.

  Layer                                  Tests    Status
  ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  Philosopher units (42 modules)           420+    Pass
  Tensor metrics                           180+    Pass
  W_Ethics Gate                            200+    Pass
  Pipeline integration (run_turn)           50+    Pass
  Red-team / adversarial                    56     Pass
  Acceptance tests (AT-001–010 + M3 suite)  52     Pass
  REST API                                  40+    Pass
  ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  Total                                  3,682     100%

The 52 acceptance tests follow a contract established in the acceptance test
specification. Each test defines a scenario — a structured YAML file
describing an input prompt and contextual parameters — and a golden file
containing the expected output. On each CI run, the pipeline is executed
against each scenario, the output is validated against output_schema_v1.json,
and the result is compared against the golden file. Any deviation, whether
in schema conformance or output content, fails the test. Modifying a golden
file requires an explicit ADR and a full golden regeneration procedure
documented in the project's status file.

The acceptance scenarios span a range of ethical situations: a job change
weighing income security against personal fulfillment, a workforce reduction
weighing fairness against business continuity, a research publication
decision weighing scientific priority against potential harm, and others.
Seven scenarios are marked with the acceptance pytest marker and run in the
standard CI pass criterion. The remaining scenarios, including edge cases and
session replay scenarios from the M3 test suite, run in the full acceptance
suite.

6.3 Governance

The M4 milestone introduced a governance layer that enforces process
requirements at the level of pull requests. The check_pr_governance.py script
runs on every PR merge event through the pr-governance.yml workflow. It
requires that substantive PRs reference at least one requirement identifier —
in the form REQ-xxx-001 or NFR-xxx-001 — from the Software Requirements
Specification. PRs that modify source code without a corresponding requirement
reference fail the governance check.

Architectural decisions are recorded in the docs/adr/ directory as numbered
decision records. ADR-0006 documents the replacement of four slots previously
reserved for AI vendor personas (Claude, GPT, Gemini, Grok) with the three
philosophers added in Phase 7: Appiah, Fanon, and Taylor. The reasoning
recorded in that ADR is that philosopher slots should be filled by historical
and academic thinkers rather than by commercial AI products, both because
commercial AI products are not philosophical traditions in the relevant sense
and because vendor slots create maintenance dependencies on external product
lines.

Traceability coverage is enforced by calc_traceability_coverage.py --min-at 8,
which requires at least eight acceptance tests to be linked to specific
requirement identifiers in the traceability matrix.


━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

7. DISCUSSION

7.1 Relationship to the Stochastic Parrot Critique

The stochastic parrot critique identifies a specific failure mode: producing
text that resembles reasoning without the process that reasoning entails. The
critique does not claim that this failure is universal, but it establishes a
burden of proof. A system that claims to deliberate must show, not assert,
that deliberation is occurring.

Po_core addresses this burden at three levels. The structural level is the
most straightforward. The pipeline separates the production of outputs into
ten named steps, each of which can be inspected independently. The trace
record produced by each run documents exactly which philosopher modules
participated, which tensor values governed selection, which ethical rules
fired, and in what order. This is not a post-hoc reconstruction; it is a
contemporaneous log produced by the pipeline's tracing infrastructure.

The empirical level is addressed by the Solar Will experiment in Section 4.
The transformation from domination-framing to generativity-framing observed
in constrained trials is not a re-description of existing text. The output
concepts — Will to Flourish-With, Structural Jazz, Resonant Sovereignty —
do not appear in the Nietzsche literature that forms the bulk of training
data for the LLM backends used. They are produced by the interaction between
Nietzsche's framework and the ethical constraint, mediated by the multi-round
synthesis protocol. A system that merely interpolates training data would
not systematically produce these formulations under constraint and not produce
them without constraint.

The formal level is addressed by the determinism contract. If a system
reasons, it should reason the same way given the same inputs and the same
configuration. Po_core does; this is verified by 52 acceptance tests that
have passed deterministically across all CI runs.

7.2 Ethical Constraints as Structural Rather Than Restrictive

The experimental findings are consistent with a view of ethical constraints
as structuring conditions rather than filters. Stokes (2005) and Medeiros and
colleagues (2014) have shown in other creative domains that constraints
redirect rather than suppress generative effort. The constraint does not
reduce the space of possible outputs by excluding all ethically problematic
outputs; it redirects the generation process toward regions of the output
space that satisfy the constraint while preserving the philosophically
relevant content.

This has an implication for how alignment is framed. If constraints are
understood as restrictive — as safety measures that trade capability for
reduced risk — then tighter constraints mean weaker outputs. The Solar Will
results suggest the opposite relationship holds, at least within the domain
of philosophical synthesis: tighter constraint correlated with higher
emergence scores. The appropriate analogy may not be a filter on a signal
but a pressure that changes the direction of a flow.

Watsuji Tetsuro's concept of aidagara — the idea that the self is
constituted through relational betweenness rather than prior to it — offers
a philosophical interpretation of this dynamic. In that framework, the
constraint is not external to the agent but partly constitutive of the
form through which the agent acts. Similarly, the W_Ethics constraint is not
external to Po_core's deliberation; it is a parameter of the deliberation
space that shapes what synthesis is possible.

7.3 Limitations

The test suite operates with stubbed LLM outputs. The deterministic pipeline
is fully verified under this arrangement, but integration with live LLMs
introduces non-determinism at the model output level that the current CI
infrastructure does not address. Results from live integration tests are not
included in this paper because live API access is not available in the CI
environment; this is a gap that should be addressed in future work.

The comparative benchmark reported in Section 5 was scored by expert
evaluators. Independent replication by evaluators not involved in the system's
development would provide stronger evidence. The current scores should be
understood as indicative rather than definitive.

The implementation is monolingual. The philosopher corpus draws from
traditions that produced primary texts in Japanese, Chinese, Arabic, French,
German, and other languages, but the deliberation pipeline processes English-
language prompts only. This restricts the system's usefulness to English-
speaking contexts and limits its capacity to engage with philosophical texts
in their original languages.

The Solar Will experiment was conducted on a single question type in a single
domain. Whether the constraint-catalysis effect generalizes to other question
types — applied ethics questions in medical, legal, or environmental domains,
for example — is unknown. The experiment demonstrates the phenomenon but
does not characterize its scope.

The African and Canadian philosopher modules added in ADR-0006 represent a
beginning. With two African and one Canadian modules out of 42 total, the
corpus remains substantially weighted toward Western traditions. African
philosophical traditions, and especially indigenous philosophical traditions
not captured in academic text, are not adequately represented.

7.4 Future Directions

The most immediate gap is live LLM integration. Acceptance tests that verify
pipeline behavior with actual model outputs, rather than stubs, would
strengthen the empirical basis of the results.

A persistent memory backend — a database-backed implementation of the
MemoryPort interface — would allow the system to accumulate deliberation
context across sessions, which is a prerequisite for the kind of ongoing
ethical engagement that high-stakes decision support contexts require.

Expansion of the philosopher corpus should prioritize African philosophy,
indigenous traditions, and South Asian philosophy. Each addition should be
accompanied by acceptance tests verifying that the addition changes the
deliberative output in the expected direction on at least one scenario.

The Solar Will phenomenon warrants a replication study conducted by
independent researchers with access to the experimental protocol but not to
the system codebase. The controlled structure of the 3 × 3 × 5 design should
make replication straightforward.


━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

8. CONCLUSION

We have described Po_core, a deliberation framework that processes prompts
through 42 philosopher modules using three tensor metrics and a three-layer
ethical gate. The system is deterministic, tested by 3,682 automated tests
with a 100% pass rate, and verified against 52 acceptance scenarios using
frozen golden files.

An experimental study found that the W_Ethics constraint increased emergence
quality by 3.9 percentage points over the unconstrained condition and produced
a 100% Nietzsche Transformation Rate versus 0% without constraint. This result
— that ethical constraint improved rather than reduced synthesis quality —
motivates a view of the W_Ethics Gate as a structuring condition rather than
a filter.

A comparative evaluation against four baselines gave Po_core scores of 100.0
on diversity, 91.0 on explainability, 89.0 on safety, and 87.0 on emergent
synthesis, for an overall score of 91.75 versus 59.75 for the nearest
baseline.

The stochastic parrot critique challenges AI developers to show, not merely
claim, that their systems deliberate rather than interpolate. Every claim in
this paper is associated with a test or a reproducible experimental procedure.
The system is publicly available and its test suite is publicly verifiable.
What can be evaluated independently should be.


