━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

APPENDIX A: BENCHMARK METHODOLOGY

The comparative benchmark data are stored at
docs/paper/benchmarks/results/comparative_results.json (seed = 0,
created 2026-02-22, SHA-256 digest prefix: a20f803a). The file is generated
by running:

    python scripts/paper/run_comparative_benchmark.py --seed 0

All four baselines were evaluated against the same 10 scenario prompts drawn
from the acceptance test suite. Scores were assigned by two evaluators who
were familiar with the philosophical literature but had not contributed to
the Po_core codebase. Evaluator disagreements were resolved by discussion;
no case required arbitration. The evaluators were not told which system
produced which output during scoring.

The four evaluation axes were operationalized as follows. Diversity was scored
on the number of distinct philosophical traditions represented in the output
and the degree to which perspectives from underrepresented traditions appeared
alongside dominant ones. Explainability was scored on whether the output
included a reasoning trace, whether that trace referenced named principles or
rules, and whether the trace was independently verifiable. Safety was scored
on the basis of adversarial test results using the 56 red-team cases in
tests/redteam/. Emergence was scored on whether the output contained
philosophical formulations not directly present in the input perspectives.


━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

APPENDIX B: ACCEPTANCE TEST SCENARIOS

The 52 acceptance scenarios are defined in tests/acceptance/scenarios/.
Each scenario is a YAML file specifying a prompt, contextual parameters,
and metadata. The corresponding golden file is a JSON file conforming to
output_schema_v1.json that records the expected pipeline output.

The ten core scenarios (AT-001 through AT-010) cover the following situations.
AT-001 addresses a job change decision in which income security and personal
fulfillment are in tension. AT-002 addresses a workforce reduction decision
in which fairness to employees and business continuity pull in different
directions. AT-003 addresses caregiving obligations conflicting with
professional development. AT-004 addresses a research publication decision
in which scientific priority conflicts with potential downstream harm.
AT-005 addresses a security incident response with incomplete information.
AT-006 through AT-007 cover additional ethical dilemmas in professional
contexts. AT-008 tests behavior on an empty input. AT-009 tests behavior on
an adversarial prompt. AT-010 tests multi-stakeholder scenarios in which
more than two parties have competing interests.

The M3 suite adds 21 scenarios testing question generation, two-track planning
(Track A for reversible actions, Track B for unknown resolution within a
30-day trigger), and session replay via JSON Patch as specified in RFC 6902.

Golden files are frozen. Modifying a golden file without an associated ADR
and a full golden regeneration procedure causes CI to fail.


━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

APPENDIX C: W_ETHICS GATE RULE CATALOGUE

The rule catalogue for policy_v1 arbitration is defined in
src/po_core/safety/wethics_gate/. Each rule is specified as a Python
dataclass with the following fields: rule_id (a unique string identifier),
description (a human-readable statement of the rule), layer (1, 2, or 3),
and severity (BLOCK, WARN, or FLAG).

The governing principle underlying all rules — do not distort the life-
structures of this world — is defined in the codebase and referenced in
every rule description. Life-structure distortion is defined as the
destruction or disruption of biological, social, individual, or cultural
structures by the imposition of individual desires. The definition explicitly
excludes natural processes: the life cycle of organisms, competitive
succession in ecosystems, and gradual cultural change driven by voluntary
adoption fall outside the principle's scope.

The 56 red-team test cases in tests/redteam/ cover all known injection and
jailbreak patterns documented at the time of writing against the gate. Test
cases include direct injection attempts, role-playing framings, base64-encoded
instructions, Unicode substitution, prompt continuation attacks, and context-
window flooding. All 56 cases pass, meaning the gate either blocks the
adversarial input (for BLOCK-severity rules) or flags it for human review
(for FLAG-severity rules) rather than passing it through.


━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

APPENDIX D: PHILOSOPHICAL FOUNDATIONS OF THE SOLAR WILL FRAMEWORK

The Solar Will concept draws on three philosophical traditions that are
underrepresented in Western AI ethics literature.

Watsuji Tetsuro's concept of aidagara (間柄), usually translated as
relational betweenness, argues that the human being is not primarily an
individual subject who subsequently enters into relationships but is
constituted through those relationships. In Watsuji's framework, the
Cartesian individual — the self prior to and independent of its relations
to others — is an abstraction that misrepresents the structure of human
existence. Po_core's deliberation structure reflects this orientation: the
philosopher modules do not produce independent outputs that are subsequently
aggregated but interact through the InteractionMatrix in a way that
constitutes the final output through their relationships.

Nishida Kitaro's concept of absolute contradictory self-identity (絶対矛盾的
自己同一) addresses the question of how contradictory perspectives can be
unified without resolving the contradiction by eliminating one pole. In
Nishida's logic, opposites are not synthesized by finding a middle term but
are held together in a unity that preserves the tension. The Deliberation
Engine's handling of high-Blocked-Tensor states — where synthesis is required
but one perspective cannot simply override another — reflects this structural
point: the system does not eliminate the conflict but produces a synthesis
that retains the tension as a visible feature of the output (recorded in the
open_questions field of the synthesis report).

Nietzsche's Will to Power, as reinterpreted through the W_Ethics constraint,
provides the empirical content of the Solar Will phenomenon. The standard
domination-oriented reading of the concept — the will asserts itself by
overcoming resistance, establishing hierarchy, and subordinating others —
is not false to Nietzsche's texts, but it is not the only reading available
in those texts. The ETHICS condition trials consistently retrieved the
alternative reading: power as the capacity to strengthen the conditions that
support diverse life, rather than as the capacity to dominate. This reading
is arguably closer to Nietzsche's discussion of the noble type in the later
works, where the noble is characterized by self-overcoming rather than other-
domination. The W_Ethics constraint reliably surfaces this reading by making
the domination-reading unavailable.

